# Cline Rules - Contra Clone

## Project Overview

A browser-based 2D side-scrolling run-and-gun game inspired by the classic NES Contra, built with Phaser 3.9x (Arcade Physics), TypeScript 5.x (strict mode), Vite, Vitest, and Playwright.

## Tech Stack

- Framework: Phaser 3.9x (Arcade Physics)
- Language: TypeScript 5.x (strict mode)
- Build: Vite 5
- Unit Tests: Vitest
- E2E Tests: Playwright
- Hosting: Cloudflare Pages
- CI/CD: GitHub Actions

## Commands

- npm run dev: Vite dev server (port 3000)
- npm run build: tsc + vite build
- npm run preview: Vite preview
- npm run lint: tsc --noEmit
- npm run test: Vitest run
- npm run test:watch: Vitest watch mode
- npm run test:e2e: Playwright smoke tests

## Coding Conventions

### Naming

- Classes / Components: PascalCase (StageScene, Player, MachineGun)
- Interfaces: PascalCase with optional I prefix (IState, IWeaponStrategy, EventMap)
- Methods / Functions: camelCase (transition, acquire, setupColliders)
- Variables: camelCase (activeCount, currentState)
- Constants / Enums: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (GAME_WIDTH, PLAYER_SPEED)
- Files: PascalCase for classes, camelCase for utilities (StateMachine.ts, playerInput.ts)
- Scene keys: lowercase (boot, stage, mainmenu)
- Event names: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (PLAYER_DIED, STAGE_COMPLETED)

### Formatting

- Indentation: 2 spaces (no tabs)
- Quotes: Double quotes for strings
- Semicolons: Required
- Trailing commas: Yes on multiline objects/arrays
- Braces: Same line
- Arrow functions: Prefer over function keyword for callbacks
- Explicit return types: Required on all public methods and exported functions
- const over let: Always use const unless rebinding is needed

### File Structure

Each file starts with a comment identifying its path:
- // scenes/BootScene.ts
- // core/StateMachine.ts

### Imports

- Use relative imports with explicit extensions
- Group: 3rd party then internal (separated by blank line)
- Named exports preferred over default exports

Example:
import Phaser from "phaser";
import { ServiceLocator } from "../core/ServiceLocator";

### TypeScript

- strict mode enabled - no any types (use unknown instead)
- Prefer interface over type for object shapes
- Use type for unions, intersections
- No unused locals or parameters
- Every code path must return (noImplicitReturns)

## Architecture Patterns

### Dependency Rules
1. Systems depend on Entities and Managers. Entities never import Scenes or Systems.
2. Managers are singletons via ServiceLocator, registered in BootScene.
3. Event Bus is the only cross-layer dependency.

### Design Patterns

- Service Locator (core/ServiceLocator.ts): Static registry for manager singletons
- State Machine (core/StateMachine.ts): Generic FSM for Player, Enemy, Boss
- Observer / Event Bus (core/EventBus.ts): Typed event emitter
- Object Pool (core/ObjectPool.ts): Reuses bullets, explosions, particles
- Factory (EnemyFactory.ts): Maps type strings to constructors
- Strategy: Weapons use IWeaponStrategy; AI uses IAiBehavior

### Scene Flow
Boot -> Preload -> MainMenu -> Stage -> Boss -> Victory/GameOver
HudScene runs parallel via scene.launch

### Entity Hierarchy
BaseEntity (Phaser.Physics.Arcade.Sprite, implements IEntity)
  - Player (StateMachine, WeaponSystem, i-frames, lives)
  - Enemy (abstract: IAiBehavior + StateMachine)
  - Boss (abstract: multi-phase StateMachine)
  - Pickup (overlap-triggered effect)
  - Projectile (pooled, owner tracking)

### Systems
CollisionSystem, SpawnSystem, WeaponSystem, DamageSystem, CameraSystem

### Managers
AssetManager, AudioManager, SaveManager, SceneManager

## Performance Constraints

- Arcade Physics only (not Matter.js)
- No Math.random() in gameplay - use seeded RNG
- Stage-specific atlas loading
- Object pooling for bullets, explosions, particles
- Max 12 concurrent enemies, 60 pooled bullets
- Texture atlases max 2048x2048
- Desktop: 60 FPS | Mobile: 30 FPS min

## Testing

- Unit tests (Vitest): Pure logic (StateMachine, EventBus, ObjectPool, WeaponSystem, SaveManager)
- E2E tests (Playwright): Scene transitions, canvas rendering
- Test files in tests/unit/ or tests/e2e/

## Git Commit Format

- feat(player): add jump mechanics
- feat(weapon): implement spread gun
- fix(enemy): fix spawn timing issue
- refactor(audio): simplify manager

## Key Rules

1. Read Memory Bank before architectural decisions or starting new phases.
2. Never break dependency rules: Systems -> Entities/Managers.
3. Register EventBus handlers in create() and unregister in shutdown().
4. Use ServiceLocator for managers.
5. Understand existing code before adding new files.
6. Use seeded RNG in gameplay.
7. Check Progress file before starting work.
8. Run lint and test after making changes.
9. New entities extend BaseEntity (extends Phaser.Physics.Arcade.Sprite).
10. Weapons implement IWeaponStrategy; AI implements IAiBehavior.
11. Use console.log("[SceneName] message") format in scenes.
12. Production build must succeed before task completion.

## Definition of Done

- Build passes (npm run build)
- Lint passes (npm run lint)
- Tests pass (npm run test)
- No console errors
- No FPS regression
- Documentation updated
- Code follows conventions
